The more I think about it, single-page apps usually don't rely on cookies for auth state. You usually do an auth process, get an auth token and then pass that auth token/header or something in consecutive calls. However, we still want to have the feature that people who leave their email (e.g. leaving the company and LDAP) should be "kicked out". So there has to be some renewal since that's what we use to see if the user is still has access to the email she authenticated with. 

So normally, if I work against the GitHub API, if my token gets revoked I'll eventually get a `403 Forbidden` or something similar if I keep making calls with an old auth token.

