Stdlib datetime objects behave intuitively if you understand what they are.  They do not attempt to model any absolute notion of a "point in time."  They just model a clock with seven hands: year through microsecond.  A timedelta is a knob that allows you to get a new configuration of  hands and tzinfo is a label that helps interpret what the given configuration of hands means.  Morever, a datetime instance is a clock that is stopped.  An instance showing 1970-01-01T00:00:00.000000 now will show the same time in an hour and in 30 years unless it is destroyed.

The timedelta arithmetic is just a convenient set of elementary operations that can be used to model passing of time and timezone changes, but it does not by itself attempt to model what people do to their clocks in different parts of the world.

