I just found this, obviously after asking questions on the forum.
My requirement was to extract *multiple* feature maps from an image. My solution so far is [this](https://discuss.pytorch.org/t/accessing-any-feature-of-pretrained-net-by-name/15568/2?u=mmcm)

```python
class VGG19FeatureExtractor(nn.Module):
  def __init__(self, net, targets):
    super(VGG19FeatureExtractor, self).__init__()
    self.features = net.features
    self.classifier = net.classifier
    if isinstance(targets, int):
      self.targets = {targets}  # TODO: make this nice strings
      self.is_list = False
    else:
      self.targets = set(targets)  # TODO: make this nice strings
      self.is_list = True
    max_index = len(self.features) + len(self.classifier)
    for t in targets:
      if not 0 <= t < max_index:
        raise ValueError(f'Invalid target index {t}. Should be within [0, {max_index})')

  def forward(self, x):
    results = list()
    for i, module in enumerate(self.features):
      x = module(x)
      if i in self.targets:
        print(f'{i}\t{module}')
        results.append(x.clone())
        if len(results) == len(self.targets):
          if self.is_list:
            return results
          else:
            return results[0]
    x = x.view(x.shape[0], -1)
    
    i_ = len(self.features)  # classifier numbers are numbered starting from this
    for i, module in enumerate(self.classifier):
      x = module(x)
      if i + i_ in self.targets:
        results.append(x.clone())
        print(f'{i+i_}\t{module}')
        if len(results) == len(self.targets):
          if self.is_list:
            return results
          else:
            return results[0]
    raise RuntimeError('should have returned before here. what happened?!')
```

Not pretty, I know...
My point being that since I want to extract multiple features, the solutions like passing an `up_to_layer` parameter don't apply. Obviously, this may be a corner case.

I agree with @ozancaglayan that for common architectures like VGG19, referencing layers by their commonly used names would be great. 
Also, I know that the decision to not have a `Flatten` or `BatchFlatten` module [is a conscious one](https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/issues/2118) but here it would really reduce code complexity to have one, since all vgg models could very reasonably be expressed as *one* `Sequential` without any shoehorning.

Currently to access the PyObject to invoke it is just a dict lookup on the globals dict. Doing anything else would require additional processing, the most practical way to do that would be to simply eval the statement that is passed to invoke. That makes me nervous from a performance perspective, particularly for the simple case where it is just a global object, I would be hesitant to add the eval if it is going to noticeably slow down everyone currently using invoke.

I have not looked deep enough to see if my performance concerns are legitimate or completely premature. I'm sure python eval is very optimized and the performance change might be negligible compared to all the other back and forth we are doing with JNI. Currently this is not a high priority for me to investigate, but I am open to a pull request if anyone else has some time to look into it. 

